ncer Vanlaan, I walked slowly to the Innkeep.  I had once been a worshipper of the Whore, Erollisi, goddess of Love, in what was, quite literally, another life.  I had been trained to make men fall in love with me; or, to put it another way, I was trained in bringing out the beast within a man.  I slunk sensously towards him, and raised my violet eyes to him.  Using my most wanton sounding voice, I whispered, &quot;Are you aware of the gifts that my god gives me?  Even with the protection of those little paladins, your soul would be tormented in the Plane of Hate before your god even knew you were dead.&quot;<br><br>As the color bleached from his skin, I pulled a purse from my belt.  &quot;But that's not necessary, is it?  I believe that I have enough here to make us all forget our differences for the night.  My companion is cold, and I will not allow anything to happen to him.&quot;  A few platinum coins was all we needed to buy a spot by the fire to warm ourselves outside, and a few tankards of the house slop to forget the chill inside.<br> <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk(Ayonae Ro Server)</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A> at: 1/5/01 6:51:16 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucasidy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Casidy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Regular Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/1/01 6:06:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Casidy had been sitting in the corner of the room, playing. She was a bard, and it was her night to entertain the audience. She made good tips in this place, and the later and drunker the audience got the easier they were parted with their money.<br><br>She had noticed the tension as the dark ones had entered the Inn, and how the paladins had covered their swords with their hands in preparation.<br><br>Fights were bad for business, and bad for her tips.<br><br>She saw the dark elf slide up close to the Innkeep and whisper something, no doubt a threat of some sort to his ear, as the color drained from his face. Casidy was not the only one to see this, the tension in the room could be cut with a knife.<br><br>Sighing softly to herself, why does it always have to happen on my night she thought. A plan quickly formed in her mind how to dissipate the building tension, she just hoped that the dark ones would go along with her plan.<br><br>While she had her resolve firmly in hand, she rose quickly and ran up to embrace the one speaking at the counter. Throwing her arms around the strangers neck, she purred out &quot;Cousin, what brings you to these parts, and on my entertaining night?&quot; winking softly to the person in her arms, but feeling a blade slide up to touch her ribs. <br><br>&quot;Have you been so desiring of my music to travel so far and long to hear me play?&quot; Her eyes pleading with the dark one to follow her story.<br><br>Turning to the Innkeep, Casidy threw on her best smile. &quot;Innkeep, a round for my cousins, and the best room in the house. I, of course, will cover the cost.&quot;<br><br> <p><br>---------------------------<br>- Silent, Deadly...           -<br>- Yeah Right...                  -<br>---------------------------<br><br>~ Casidy </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/1/01 8:12:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> When the bard suddenly clutched for me, my blade almost leapt to my hand.  Almost.  An admonishing glance from my master was enough to remind me of my place... and the statements I had made already.  I had requested peace, despite the color of my skin; should I not now offer the same?  Carefully, I released my claymore's hilt, and slipped from her grip.  I have no doubt that her puny dagger would be ineffective against my dwarven-forged banded mail, but dwarves have a tendency to offer their services to anyone... yet leave certain things unsaid, or undone.<br><br>&quot;Yes, ah, my... lady,&quot; I said, trying not to let my instinctive feelings show.  &quot;We are quite fond of... the... ah, music here.&quot;<br><br>My master, always the tactful one, added, &quot;Quite fine music, as well.  Perhaps some day you could play to our people in Neriak.&quot;<br><br>I sized up my opponent (perhaps, at the time, not the most accurate wording, but the only one I know to use.)  It didn't seem like she would pose a challenge, but one can never be certain.  Besides, I had demanded peace, and it was only proper that I offered that I demanded.<br><br>&quot;Perhaps you could spin us a tale,&quot; I said to her as I brought our drinks to Vanlaans table.  Suddenly, an idea caught me, and I smiled to myself.  &quot;After all, I am merely a dark elf, and no songsmith such as yourself.  I'm certain that you would be able to awe me with tales of your life.  Certainly, one such as I could never match your tales.&quot;<br><br>Vanlaan gave me an odd look, which I ignored.  It was likely that I had a thing or two to show my master; after all, he had never attended my sermons to the Dismal Rage.  It was not the night for combat, but that did not mean it wasn't a night for competition... <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk(Ayonae Ro Server)</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A> at: 1/1/01 8:20:27 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Drahknar</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/3/01 5:47:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> story continued</span><hr size=1> In one of the darker corners of the inn, a robed figure sat watching the display.  He saw the reaction of the so-called &quot;paladins&quot; when the &quot;dark ones&quot;, as the others called them, walked in.  He had been following them for the last few days trying to find an opportune moment to speak with them and was not about to allow them to come to harm.  Beneath the robes his hands began to glow as he quitely wove a spell.  Nervously his tail twitched beneath his robe and he almost lept from his seat when the bard approached them.  But nothing happened.  The bard embraced the one &quot;dark one&quot; and though everyone seemed surprised, no one made a move against them.  So he quietly sipped his mead and waited for his chance to speak with them.  He hoped that though they be of different race, the fact they worshiped the same gods would be enough to convince them to afford him solace in their city, as well as access to the wealth of dark knowledge that they are rumored to posess.  He had waiting four weeks to find a member of the &quot;dark ones&quot; he could speak to...he was patient enough to wait a little while longer. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucasidy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Casidy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Regular Poster</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/3/01 8:53:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Walking with this new unlikely friend to a table, Casidy glanced around the tavern smiling and flirting with many of the occupants. Her popularity here, had secured these two a room, and safety atleast for the moment.<br><br>&quot;A tale you say, well I can certainly weave a tale to entertain.&quot; Casidy smiled warmly at the challenge. It was a challenge wasn't it, she had thought that was the intent behind the message. Bah, how could anyone ever hope to compete at tale weaving save for another bard, this was after all her profession. <br><br>Thinking to humor this traveler, Casidy spoke softly, &quot;But surely you must have many tales to tell yourself with all your recent travels, that a mere bard could hardly hope to compete with.&quot;  <p><br>---------------------------<br>- Silent, Deadly...           -<br>- Yeah Right...                  -<br>---------------------------<br><br>~ Casidy </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 4:17:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> I smiled warmly (or, at least, I hope it was warmly; it's hard to be certain sometimes.)  This young fool was determined to take my challenge, and expected me to falter.  I took a deep swig of the offered ale, wincing at its bitterness (the taverns in Neriak would never serve such swill), and began.<br><br>&quot;I was not always as I appear now.  Once, hard as it may be to believe, I was a mere human, one of the stinking rabble that infest Freeport.  Among them, I could have been royalty, had I chosen; instead, I learned where my place truly was, in Innoruuk's service.&quot;<br><br>I am always amused by the various hand gestures used when I mention the Father's name.<br><br>&quot;But I see no need to bore you with tales of my childhood.  Most prefer tales of wars, of fierce battles between good and evil.  I, however, know nothing about good and evil, only the Truth, and the Lies.  But again, I digress.<br><br>It was early in my career as a Champion of the Father when I decided that it was time to gaze upon His Holy City.  I therefore met with the elders of the Dismal Rage, our Church, and pleaded with them to allow me to make myself useful.  Within weeks, I received the response; I was to report to the Bridge in Nektulos (easily reached by simply following the road) to meet with a fellow Champion in His Service.<br><br>&quot;This was when I met Val'khan, assistant to the great L'vanon, both of the Church of the Firstborn.  It seems that Val'khan was in need of armor and, as I had been trained as a seamstress in my youth, I was quite adept at putting together ruined pelts to make a kind of tattered armor.  Through Val'khan, I would go on to meet my current Master.<br><br>&quot;With them as my guides, I was led through the Foreign Quarter, where the slaves - mostly humans, such as I once was - and the visitors from Grobb and Oggok - spent their time.  The horrific scent...<br><br>&quot;From there, we visited the Commons, where the bank could be found.  Although I was eyed with disdain by the guards due to the lightness of my skin, they made no motion against me.  We therefore continued on to the Lodge of the Dead, where the Shadowknights and Necromancers trained.  At the gates were a trio of ghouls, blessed creatures of Innoruuk raised to do His service.  It was the first time I had ever seen ghouls, and I stood in amazement and awe as they began racing from their post, no doubt to protect the Lodge from some unwanted visitor.<br><br>&quot;Although most of my memories of the seconds that followed are mercifully brief, when I regained conciousness, Val'khan did look quite embarrassed.&quot;<br><br>I looked around with a smile and drained the last of my drink.  &quot;Keep that in mind, should you visit the beautiful city of Neriak - no matter which god you worship, those not of Teir'dal descent are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  not</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> welcome beyond Neriak's Third Gate.&quot; <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk(Ayonae Ro Server)</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A> at: 1/4/01 4:17:37 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=vanlaan>Vanlaan</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 4:34:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: story continued</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> In one of the darker corners of the inn, a robed figure sat watching the display. He saw the reaction of the so-called &quot;paladins&quot; when the &quot;dark ones&quot;, as the others called them, walked in. He had been following them for the last few days trying to find an opportune moment to speak with them and was not about to allow them to come to harm. Beneath the robes his hands began to glow as he quitely wove a spell. Nervously his tail twitched beneath his robe and he almost lept from his seat when the bard approached them. But nothing happened. The bard embraced the one &quot;dark one&quot; and though everyone seemed surprised, no one made a move against them. So he quietly sipped his mead and waited for his chance to speak with them. He hoped that though they be of different race, the fact they worshiped the same gods would be enough to convince them to afford him solace in their city, as well as access to the wealth of dark knowledge that they are rumored to posess. He had waiting four weeks to find a member of the &quot;dark ones&quot; he could speak to...he was patient enough to wait a little while longer.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>As a magic user, Vanlaan was trained to recognize fellow magic users.  Quietly scoping the tavern, Vanlaan noticed the robed figure in the corner almost immediately.  It wasn't hard to notice the fact that no one sat at any of the surrounding tables.  Vanlaan looked over at Aedare.  Although Aedare was quite capable of taking care of herself, Vanlaan was responsible for her actions and didn't want her causing trouble.  Not here.  Not now.  They needed to keep a low profile for the time being.  Aedare was occupied with teasing the bard.  Well, that was fine.  There shouldn't be too much harm in competition tale-telling.  He had to feel sorry for the bard though; she really had no idea what she was getting herself into.<br><br>Deciding that Aedare was occupied in a non-violent way, Vanlaan got up and made his way towards the back of the tavern.  He tried to act casual, but a Dark Elf Necromancer is anything but inconspicuous.  He mentally shrugged.  'Oh well,' he thought, 'I certainly won't draw anymore attention then our entrance already drew.'  As he approached the table, he noticed the lone figure was watching him.  If he wasn't mistaken, there was a lizard snout poking out from underneath the cowl of the stranger's hood.  'More and more interesting,' he thought.<br><br>He sat down at the table and studied the stranger for a moment.  &quot;Can I buy you a drink?&quot;, he asked.  &quot;I noticed you watching my companion and I as we came in.  Is there something I can help you with?&quot;  He sat back and took a sip of the swill this Inn labeled ale.  He was very interested to hear what the stranger had to say. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=qwik>Qwik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 8:31:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: story continued</span><hr size=1> just as a kunak rhino in an erudite china shop a taller man with an air of playfullness to him comes down the stairs loudly from the rooms on the second floor. glancing around still trying to get his bearings after a rest from training all day with his brothers of the ashen order he sits down with a flask of mead with a loud well deserved sigh. surveying the room he notices an uneasy crowd all murmering about something he just couldnt seem to make out.  Grinning he sees a delightful treat in that of a master songreaver only she seems quite pre-occupied to be bothered with his requests for one of his favorite songs to remind him of days long past.  Dispite it being painfully obvious that she is busy with a very strange looking lass he rises out of his char and walks over to her with a smirk on his face and whispers &lt;when your done with your friend care to play a song to fill this tired body with some warmth that the fire and mead just cant manage?&gt; with a playfull nod he turns around and goes back by the fire and takes his place back in the chair and slips back into his own thoughts. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/udahrkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dahrkon</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 4:19:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: story continued</span><hr size=1> One of the &quot;Dark Ones&quot; finaly noticed that they were being watched and approached.  It appeared that he would not have to wait much longer to speak with them...not much longer at all.  However, for as much as he had been trying to speak with them, he dreaded it.  Though he had a good understanding of Common in the time he had been away from home, it was physicly painfull for him to form the words.  And this he did not looke forward to.  But try he must.  He needed allies in this land.<br><br>Quitely he watched as the one he had learned was named Vanlaan aproached.  He sat down next to him and said nothing at first.  They both sat in silence, eyeing each other up.  Then finaly Vanlaan spoke.  <br>&quot;Can I buy you a drink?&quot;.  The question was completely unexpected.  Drakhnar chuckled slightly and the question that followed was more the one he expected.  &quot;I noticed you watching my companion and I as we came in. Is there something I can help you with?&quot; Vanlaan said.  Drahnar thought for a second, he had to choose his words carefully.  Finaly he spoke in a tone he hoped was low enough that the others in the Inn would not hear.  &quot;Yesss, I have been following for sssome time.  I have been wanting to sssspeak with you.  Firssst I want you to know that I mean you and your friend no harm.  I sssimply asssk that you hear me out.  Asss for the drink, I would like another yesss.&quot;<br><br><br>&lt;Note: I used the name Drakhnar here before I registered...was having difficulty doing so.  But when I finaly got in to register, the name was taken.&gt;<br><br>Drakhnar<br>3rd Circle Necromancer<br>The Powers that Be ~ Ayonae Ro server <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/udahrkon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dahrkon</A> at: 1/4/01 4:21:55 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucasidy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Casidy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 8:47:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Casidy listened to the tale woven before her. She was indeed impressed with this ones ability to weave a tale. <br><br>The handsome monk had snuck up behind her and touched her skin to whisper in her ear, distracting her concentration on the story. His touch had sent electric pulses down her body, and as she turned she smiled, this fellow she recognized warmly.<br><br>Returning her attention to the speaker, as she finished her tale, Casidy was intrigued. She had been taught that all gods were both correct and false, so one was no better than any other, the compassion with which this lady spoke of Innoruuk both surprised and amazed Casidy. That would be a story for another time.<br><br>Still, the challenge was left to her. It would not be overly difficult, as she had her gifts with limited magic and music to weave with her tale, as only a bard could. And that human admirer of hers had asked for something specific, well perhaps she could accommodate both requests.<br><br>Lifting her glass, she raised it before her newly met contemporary. "To your health," and with that she downed the contents.<br><br>"I have been requested to tell a tale of old, a love story with a twist." Casidy smiled and winked at Qwik. "And I think it should do nicely for entertaining, but I shall let you decide."<br><br>Pulling over one of the bar stools, and grabbing her lute, Casidy did a quick check on the instrument to be sure it had not lost its tuning and that the stings were tight.<br><br>"This is a short little tale, of a local legend. It is titled, Ace in the Spit."<br><br>With a wicked grin cast around the room, Casidy began to weave the magic that is a bards talent, to draw the attention of the room to her tale. A warmth of contentment fell over the crowd, and they began to sway to the rhythm and lyric of her voice, the lute, and the theme of the tale.<br><br><i><b> Ace in the Spit</b><br><br>In a city not far from here there lived a lad named Ace<br>The name he got, at birth, for being so fair in the face<br>He grew up wild, and on the land, as many of these parts do<br>In stature and status he grew as many the town folk knew<br><br>A vile evil came to town, and challenged the local men<br>Striking them like weeds to a scythe, baking them like hen<br>No one had the brains it seemed to banish this evil foe<br>But Ace its told, was not afraid for a plan his mind did sow<br><br>He challenged the fiend to a bake off, for the entire town.<br>If the villain failed to take the test, gods would frown.<br>As plans were laid, for the event, Ace grew sore afraid<br>His girl knew Ace couldn't bake, so a book to him she gave<br><br>She worked, teaching Ace to bake, to ready him for the event<br>A cake he would bake, like none ever seen, his hope to win<br>The day approached, the villain schemed against the cake<br>With his baking prowess, he had plans to up the stakes<br><br>The villain destroyed all ovens in town, seeking Ace's demise<br>Finding no oven to bake his cake, Ace had to improvise<br>The town folk cringed and fearing tried to stall<br>But Ace it seemed would show them all<br><br>Ace thought super fast, and altered the cake <br>And when it was done it came out great<br>And the town was saved, due to the Ace's fast wit<br>And to bake his cake he had used a spit</i><br><br>The tavern had kept the pace to her quick witted tale, one she had shared before, a trifle tale really. <br><br>Casidy set her lute down and picked up the fresh glass off mead the barkeep had brought her, and smiled.<br><br>The coins as always were brought or tossed her way near her stool, where her hat was laid.<br><br>She rose to take a sip from the cup and too address the lady at her table. "Well, theres one, and Casidy is my name, should you care for another. I have to make a round with the drinks, it is a deal I have worked out with the barkeep. He lets me play, and serve as I tend to get better tips that way." Smiling slightly as Casidy bounced behind the bar, and picked up a tray of frosty Ale, and headed towards the table with the band of paladins first. <br><br>The paladins where always ready to buy another mug, and tipped well, for the chance to have Casidy serve it to them.<br><br><br> <p><br><b><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#6699cc">---------------------------<br> Silent, Deadly         <br> Yeah, Right                  <br>---------------------------<br><br>~ Casidy Noteworthy</font></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uscaly.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scaly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/4/01 9:54:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.facelink.com/kingscaly?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Watching.....waiting.....it was bad enough Valeron sent him here of all places....<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> the Dismal Rage</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->....ever since acquiring Lucan's testimony the Militia had no love for Scaly.  Oh no...no love at all...<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Why am I here? Valeron could have atleast told me.  But no, all he said was to come and wait.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Thoughts and confusion rushed through Scaly's mind, and earlier as the &quot;Dark Ones&quot; entered, he could feel the bile rise in his throat.  The young paladins around had quickly put their hands on their hilts.  So young, so eager to fight.  So eager without truly <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> knowing</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  <br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Remain low key he said.  Don't cause any trouble regardless of what or who you see. </i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Gritting his teeth, Scaly looked deep into his emptying mug. <p>Scaly<BR><i>aging Cavalier</i><BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/5/01 4:21:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Petty though it was, I couldn't help but feel jealous of the fact that, despite the obvious superiority of my tale, the patrons were throwing coins at the wood elf.  I sighed slightly and shook my head.<br><br>&quot;A lovely song, bard,&quot; I said as I watched my master excuse himself from the proceedings, &quot;if perhaps a bit naive.  After all, if there are such things as good and evil, I doubt they'll do battle over an oven.<br><br>&quot;It reminds me of a tale I heard while we were visiting Grobb.  Now, admittedly, although there are a small number of bards in Grobb, most of them have the title of 'Snack.'&quot;  An old joke, but still a good one, which even managed to make a few of the locals crack a smile.<br><br>&quot;It seems there was a troll by the name of Shakkura, who was looking for the most wonderful feast in all of Norrath.  Now, for their hungers, trolls do not make good chefs, and so she found she had to wander on.<br><br>&quot;Nearest to Grobb, as you all may know, is Oggok, home of the Ogres.  She went to them and asked if they knew where she could find the most wonderful feast in all of Norrath.  Well, ogres are no better at cooking than trolls are, and they couldn't help her.  So, she headed to Freeport.<br><br>&quot;In Freeport, as everyone knows, is the Brownloe Bakery, where the best pastries and muffins in Norrath are available.  Perhaps, Shakkura thought, they would be able to provide me with the most wonderful feast in all of Norrath!  But, alas, for a troll, pastries are not quite the right dish.  So, she boarded the boat to Butcherblock.<br><br>&quot;In the great underground city of the dwarves, she sought a magnificent feast, but all the dwarves cared about was ale and iron.  In Felwithe, the High Elves sipped on the nectar of the gods - not exactly a trollish delicacy.  In Kelethin, they made soups and stews from foraged vegetables and meats, but it was too watery for her tastes.  And in Ak'Anon, she tried to find a feast, but the ticking made her stomach hurt too much.<br><br>&quot;Sad and despondent, she travelled back across the Ocean of Tears, and made her way to Rivervale.  And in Rivervale, she found the most magnificent feast in all of Norrath!<br><br>&quot;And that's why halflings are so much shorter than everyone else.&quot;<br><br>There was a long silence.  I noticed that Vanlaan's attempts at conversation had come to a halt, and he simply stared at me for a moment.  Then, he rolled his eyes and turned back to his conversation.<br><br>I sighed and helped myself to one of Casidy's drinks.  &quot;I suppose there's some stories that just don't translate from the original, no matter how hard you try...&quot; <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk(Ayonae Ro Server)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ucasidy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Casidy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Boardfellow</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/5/01 6:06:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Casidy listened as she carried the tray to the table of young paladins, Aedare's tale was ... well, seemed to be lacking in the quick wittedness of Casidy's own. Sighing to herself why would anyone dare try and compete with a bard at tall tales, no matter, she could help this one.<br><br>Moving quickly around the table of the young paladins, some more noble than others, she passed out drinks to those at the table, many slide a few coins to her. One overly zealous fellow, slapped her rear as she passed. "Wench, bring me another of the good mead." <br><br>Rolling her eyes as she turned and headed back to the counter, she grabbed the glass the barkeep had prepared for this special fellow, and another full tray of Ale. The men seemed more thirsty than usual this evening, maybe that as a good sign, she thought. <br><br>She returned to the table, and noticed the seasoned hero sitting off a bit from the others, his face the picture of calm. She thought she recognized this one, probably from some song or other she had learned, as he had the look of a hero about him.<br><br>Pausing to set a fresh glass in front of him, she reached out and brushed his cheek as she removed the empty. It was a subtle movement, but obviously intentional, and solicited the desired result. He looked up and stared seemingly into her very soul. Casidy looked back at him and smiled, her eyes twinked as she spoke, "Come now, this is a time for making merry. I'll not allow melancoly here to abide." <br><br>With that she returned to the bar, and filled up with a few more drinks for the remaining patrons. Stopping for a hug and pause at the table where Qwik, her favorite monk, happened to be proping his feet up on the table.<br><br>"Hi there handsome," Casidy spoke as she slide a fresh glass to him.<br> <p><br><b><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2 COLOR="#6699cc">---------------------------<br> Silent, Deadly         <br> Yeah, Right                  <br>---------------------------<br><br>~ Casidy Noteworthy</font></b></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/bayonaero.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=qwik>Qwik</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/5/01 11:58:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> If there was anything in norrath that could make Qwik smile just as a thought it was casidy. standing up to give his old friend a big hug he smiled and complimented her on yet another well spun story. &quot;i just got back from a little training in Unrest and it is wonderful timing that you should be playing in this tavern tonight, after some time in that horrid place i needed something to warm me up it is cold to say the least.&quot; &quot;so tell me&quot; he said with a smirk. &quot;how long do i have you for this evening... or should i say the tavern and its patrons have you for&quot; with a little snicker qwik proped his feet back up on the table taking a long drink out of the mug Casidy so graciously brought over to him. &quot;The night is a pup will you be gracing us with yet another tale this eve? or do i have to wait untill another night.&quot; Qwik looking around noticing that a fair ammount of eyes were on him and her probably a little jellious and a little anxious to hear another story. &quot;Dont let me keep you from your public doll .. ill be here all night&quot; And with that said he gestured to the rest of the room in hopes for yet another story. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uaedare.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aedare</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>New to the block</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/6/01 10:41:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://dntsvara.tripod.com/aedarepic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Perhaps it was too much poor quality ale; perhaps it was Vanlaan's utilizing me as a simple barmaid.  Perhaps it was simply the Father's Will.  But as the bard made her way through the room, beginning to pay more attention to the patrons than her, I reached for my blade, the room turning red in my rage.  &quot;TURN AND FACE ME!&quot; I would say.  &quot;NONE TURN FROM AEDARE AND LIVE!  IF YOU CANNOT FACE ME THROUGH WORDS, FACE ME THROUGH STEEL!&quot;<br><br>But I didn't.<br><br>Slowly, I pulled my hand away from the hilt of my claymore, and looked around, calming myself.  &quot;My hate is my shield,&quot; I whispered, and closed my eyes to calm myself.<br><br>I saw Casidy, being watched by the patrons, being cheered on for her tale, simple though it was.  I saw the paladins sitting together, telling stories of their battles.  I even saw Vanlaan, in the companionship of one of his own - a fellow scholar, at least, if not a fellow dark elf.<br><br>I was alone.<br><br>I had no family, for I had turned from the Marrs to follow in the Father's path.  The Dismal Rage had never truly listened to me, no matter how I tried to heal the rift between them and Neriak, for I was a woman attempting to do a man's job.  I now wore the skin of a dark elf, which made all of Freeport my enemy, and yet the Spires saw that within my breast beat the heart of a human, and I was spurned.  Even Vanlaan saw me as a servant, not a companion.<br><br>The hatred raged through my blood, but I kept it in check.  And in return, the Father showed me the truth.  I had not been following His path; I had been following the path that others had set for me.  L'vanon, greatest of the Dark Elves, had seen me as a way to build his armies, and then turned away when I failed.  Vanlaan saw me as a blade that he could use to regain... whatever he felt he had lost.  Once it was his sister.  Now it was his position.  He felt guilt for using me, and attempted to give me gifts, but he still needed me for his purposes.<br><br>I was no longer a priestess.  I was a warrior for the Father.  Nothing else mattered, and it was time for me to accept that.<br><br>Opening my eyes with a new clarity, I saw that all eyes were turned away from me, especially Vanlaan's.  Quietly, I gathered my supplies, and made my way from the inn. <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk(Ayonae Ro Server)</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uscaly.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scaly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/8/01 4:34:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=6.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.facelink.com/kingscaly?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60?flezbwidth=60&flezbheight=60 WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Yet another beginning...</span><hr size=1> Scaly watched as Casidy sauntered away about her business, casting a friendly smile 'ere she went.  It was good, that was just what Scaly needed to save him from his own thoughts.<br><br>The 'dark one's' tale had a rythym to it, if a bit confusing, atleast to this paladin it was.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  Watch and wait</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Valeron had said.  And so Scaly waited.  Waited and watched.  Shaking his head, and blinking hard he cleared what was before him and looked around.  <br><br>All appeared normal, the tavern was full of life.  Everyone appeared to be engaged in some conversation or another..... <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  except one</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  A lone 'dark one' was slowly rising and gathering their belongings as if to leave.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> interesting.....wasn't this one with another?  Two enter...one leaves....</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  Amused, Scaly silently watches as Casidy's &quot;competition&quot; headed for the door. <p>Scaly<BR><i>aging Cavalier</i><BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uscaly.showPublicPro